CREATED:20260219T201122Z
DESCRIPTION:In this talk\, Dr. Justin Moore will explore ongoing collabora
 tive efforts between faculty at the Wake Forest University School of Medi
 cine and administrators and clinicians across the Advocate Health system 
 aimed at accelerating the translation of evidence-based practices from cl
 inical trials (T2) into system-wide\, population‑level health improvement
 s (T4). Dr. Moore will situate this work within the broader mission of bu
 ilding a true Learning Health System\, one that continuously integrates r
 esearch\, practice\, and real‑world data to deliver better outcomes at sc
 ale. The presentation will provide an overview of key implementation scie
 nce models and frameworks that guide these translational activities\, hig
 hlighting how they can be operationalized within a large\, integrated hea
 lth system. Special attention will be given to the organizational and met
 hodological infrastructure required to support implementation at scale\, 
 including data systems\, workforce competencies\, and cross‑departmental 
 coordination mechanisms. Cultural considerations will also be addressed\,
  particularly the shifts needed for academic researchers\, operational le
 aders\, and frontline clinicians to work together in ways that are collab
 orative\, nimble\, and responsive to evolving evidence and system needs. 
 Dr. Moore will also examine financial and incentive models that enable su
 stained implementation\, scale‑up\, and spread\, recognizing that even th
 e most compelling evidence-based practices must align with real-world con
 straints and priorities. Finally\, the talk will engage directly with ten
 sions that often arise between traditional academic medicine workflows (e
 .g.\, long research timelines\, narrow scopes of inquiry\, publication‑dr
 iven incentives) and the practical realities of the American health syste
 m\, which demands rapid decision‑making\, cost‑effectiveness\, and broad 
 applicability. Dr. Moore will outline the challenges these tensions creat
 e\, as well as emerging strategies to reconcile them. Throughout the pres
 entation\, attendees will be invited to consider an evolving vision for a
  Learning Health System\, one that moves beyond aspirational concepts tow
 ard practical\, executable strategies that bring evidence to practice eff
 iciently\, equitably\, and sustainably.
DURATION:PT1H15M
